y modern government. Three leading historians of the NKVD massacres of Polish prisoners of war at Katyn, Kharkov, and Tver-now subsumed under "Katyn"-present 122 documents selected from the published Russian and Polish volumes coedited by Natalia S. Lebedeva and Wojciech Materski. The documents, with introductions and notes by Anna M. Cienciala, detail the Soviet killings, the elaborate cover-up, the admission of the truth, and the Katyn question in Soviet/Russian-Polish relations up to the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aKatyn Massacre, Katynʹ, Russia, 1940vSources. 0aKatyn Massacre, Katynʹ, Russia, 1940xSources. 70(DE-588)4163485-80(DE-627)1042478350(DE-576)209881399aKatynxMassaker2gnd 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aCienciala, Anna M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLebedeva, Natalia S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300151855423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300151855.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles